The reason for &quot;weakly pure&quot; was first discovered by Don Clugston (as far as I can tell). Suppose I have a struct with a member function:<p><pre><code>    struct S { int s; pure void set(int i) { s = i; }
</code></pre>
Now, even in a strongly pure function, I can use the weakly pure function even though it is mutating state through its arguments:<p><pre><code>    pure int foo(int i) {
        S s;
        s.set(i);
        ...
        return whatever;
    }
</code></pre>
I.e. when the effects of a weakly pure function are localized like in the example, they can be called from a strongly pure function and the strongly pure one will remain strongly pure.<p>It&#x27;s a really cool idea and it took me a bit to get it, but Don was persistent in explaining it to me :-)
